snippet.textDisplay: First of all, my thoughts and concerns are with all those ill or fighting the disease. Let us hope for positive outcomes. As a scientist, however, I am surprised it is hard to quantify the rate of non-symptomatic infections. A PCR-based test must be very sensitive. If done well, false-positive rate should be minimal. That makes it possible to screen random populations. In the first step, just calculate the ratio of those symptomatic to those positive in a PCR test, in a random screen. In the second step, build a database where you follow-up on test subjects and compare PCR-based test with tests for antibodies.
